The purpose of this post is to perform some exploratory data analysis on a very small data set provided by Kaggle.com. The project is a multiclass classification problem in which we try to classify different kinds of monsters (ghosts, ghouls, and goblins) based on various feature "measurements". This seemed like a nice little Halloween project! We will use four different classifiers in this work - logistic regression, k-nearest neighbors, support vector machines, and quadratic disriminant analysis.

Letâ€™s begin by importing the appropriate Python libraries and reading in the data.

from sklearn.discriminant_analysis import QuadraticDiscriminantAnalysis
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.grid_search import GridSearchCV
from sklearn import cross_validation
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns

import matplotlib.pyplot as mp
%matplotlib inline

df = pd.read_csv('/Users/degravek/Site/creatures/train.csv', header=0)
Let's summarize the data.

And we can examine the data in another way.
df.describe()

The data contain measurements for 371 creatures in seven columns. There are four numerical columns ('bone_length', 'rotting_flesh', 'hair_length', and 'has_soul') with values in the range [0 1], and one categorical column ('color'). It turns out that the creatures are not well separated by color (i.e., 'color' adds noise to the problem and decreases classification accuracy), and so we will drop this column.
df.drop('color', axis=1, inplace=True)
The number of numerical columns is small enough that we can make use of Seaborn's nice pairplot function to quickly visualize the data.
sns.pairplot(df.drop('id', axis=1), hue='type')

The pairplot function plots every numerical column against every other and separate them in color by creature type (ghost, ghoul, or goblin), allowing us to quickly identify obvious trends in the data. Wherever a column is plotted against itself (e.g., along the diagonal), normalized histrograms are shown.

The off-diagonal figures show that the creatures are sometimes reasonably well-separated. For example, plotting 'has_soul' vs. 'hair_length' shows reasonably good distinction between the three creatures, while plotting 'rotting_flesh' vs. 'bone_length' results in poor separation. Let's plot the data in another way.

data = df.drop(['id','type'], axis=1)

fig, axes = mp.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(6,6))
mp.tight_layout(w_pad=2.0, h_pad=2.0)

for i, column in zip(range(1,data.shape[1]+1), data.columns):
    mp.subplot(2,2,i)
    sns.boxplot(x=df['type'], y=df[column], linewidth=0.5)
    mp.ylabel(column)
    mp.ylim([0,1.1])

Again, there appears to be a clear distintion between the creature classes in each case. It is funny to think, though, that ghosts could have more rotting flesh (top right figure) than a goblin, and that a ghoul has longer hair (bottom left figure)! Let's see if the data columns are correlated.
fig, axes = mp.subplots(figsize=(7, 5))
sns.heatmap(df.drop('id', axis=1).corr(), annot=True, vmax=1, square=True, linewidths=.5)

Looking at the off-diagonal values, it appears that there is some minor correlation between, for example, 'has_soul' and 'hair_length'. However, in general, these correlation values are quite small. In any case, multicollinearity is really only a nuisance in regression problems and should not affect us in this multiclass classification case.

Since the creature types are in string format, we must first encode them before we start our classification. To do this we can use Scikit-Learn's LabelEncoder.
enc = LabelEncoder()
df['type'] = enc.fit_transform(df['type'])

Scikit-Learn's machine learning algorithms usually require features to take on similar ranges of values to yield good results. To this end, we use StandardScaler to scale the feature columns so that each has a mean of zero and unit standard deviation.

sc = StandardScaler()

feat   = sc.fit_transform(df.drop(['id','type'], axis=1).values)
target = df['type'].values

params_cv = {'C': np.linspace(0.0001,1,1000), 'solver': ['newton-cg','sag','lbfgs']}
grid = GridSearchCV(LogisticRegression(), params_cv, cv=5)
grid.fit(feat, target)
predict_LR = grid.predict(feat)
print(grid.best_params_)
print(grid.best_score_)

params_cv = {'n_neighbors': np.linspace(1,50,50).astype(int)}
grid = GridSearchCV(KNeighborsClassifier(), params_cv, cv=5)
grid.fit(feat, target)
predict_KN = grid.predict(feat)
print(grid.best_params_)
print(grid.best_score_)

params_cv = {'C': np.linspace(0.0001,0.1,1000), }
grid = GridSearchCV(SVC(kernel='rbf'), params_cv, cv=5)
grid.fit(feat, target)
predict_SV = grid.predict(feat)
print(grid.best_params_)
print(grid.best_score_)

params_cv = {'reg_param': np.linspace(0.0001,10,100)}
grid = GridSearchCV(QuadraticDiscriminantAnalysis(), params_cv, cv=5)
grid.fit(feat, target)
predict_QD = grid.predict(feat)
print(grid.best_params_)
print(grid.best_score_)

def plot_decision_regions(X, y, classifier, resolution=0.2):
    from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
    markers = ('s','x','o','^','v')
    colors = ('red','blue','lightgreen','gray','cyan')
    cmap = ListedColormap(colors[:len(np.unique(y))])

    x1_min, x1_max = X[:,0].min()-1, X[:,0].max()+1
    x2_min, x2_max = X[:,1].min()-1, X[:,1].max()+1
    xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x1_min, x1_max, resolution), np.arange(x2_min, x2_max, resolution))
    Z = classifier.predict(np.array([xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()]).T)
    Z = Z.reshape(xx1.shape)
    mp.contour(xx1, xx2, Z, alpha=0.4, cmap=cmap)
    mp.xlim([xx1.min(), xx1.max()])
    mp.ylim([xx2.min(), xx2.max()])

    for idx, cl in enumerate(np.unique(y)):
        mp.scatter(x=X[y == cl, 0], y=X[y == cl, 1], alpha=0.8, c=cmap(idx), marker=markers[idx], label=cl)

estimators = [pca_LR, pca_SV, pca_KN, pca_QD]
estimnames = ['Logistic Regression', 'Support Vector Machine', 'KNN', 'QDA']

fig, axes = mp.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(8,8))
mp.tight_layout(w_pad=2.0, h_pad=4.0)

for i in range(0,len(estimators)):
    mp.subplot(2,2,i+1)
    plot_decision_regions(feat_pca, target, classifier=estimators[i], resolution=0.2)
    mp.xlabel('First Principal Component')
    mp.ylabel('Second Principal Component')
    mp.title(estimnames[i])
    mp.xlim([min(feat_pca[:,0]),max(feat_pca[:,0])])
    mp.ylim([min(feat_pca[:,1]),max(feat_pca[:,1])])
